 <tr> 
  	<td valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="subcontentarea">
<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="1" bgcolor="#D4262F" style="margin-bottom:15px;">
  <tr> <td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="subarticleheading">THE PARALYMPICS: A LESSON IN RESILIENCE - By Paddy Cloete</td></tr>
  <tr><td valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="subarticlearea">
<P>The Paralympic Games in Beijing captured the attention of the entire nation. Everywhere you went you heard people commenting on the games. The games became part of our everyday conversations. Why did the games and the paralympic team have such an impact on us? There are many answers to this question. As a psychologist, I believe one of the answers is that the paralympic athletes symbolise what we in psychology refer to as resilience.</P>
<P><I>Resilience</I> is the phenomenon that describes an individual's capacity to maintain psychological and physical well-being in the face of adversity. Resilient people are optimistic, action-oriented people. If something goes wrong in their lives, they immediately start to think about how to make it better. Resilience does not protect you against adversity. It does, however, influence your response to adversity, and it is this resilient response to adversity that maintains psychological and physical well-being in the face of adversity. </P>
    <a href="http://newsletters.onlineinnovations.com/ironman/newsletter.asp?NewsletterID=8432&ArticleID=8432">read more...</a>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
 <tr> 
  	<td valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="subcontentarea">
<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="1" bgcolor="#D4262F" style="margin-bottom:15px;">
  <tr> <td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="subarticleheading">TRIATHLON SEASON STARTS!</td></tr>
  <tr><td valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="subarticlearea">
<table width="202" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="1" bgcolor="#D4262F" class="picturetable">
<tr><td bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><a href = "http://newsletters.onlineinnovations.com/images/news//open_big_news.asp?showcase=FLT09run clinic 045.jpg" target="_blank"><img name="pic" border="0" src="http://newsletters.onlineinnovations.com/images/news/sml_FLT09run clinic 045.jpg" style="background-color: #CCCCCC"></td></tr>
<tr><td bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><a href = "http://newsletters.onlineinnovations.com/images/news//open_big_news.asp?showcase=FLT_Logo_Final(2).jpg" target="_blank"><img name="pic" border="0" src="http://newsletters.onlineinnovations.com/images/news/sml_FLT_Logo_Final(2).jpg" style="background-color: #CCCCCC"></td></tr>
</table>
<P>Twenty-seven weeks to go and the FinishLine 2009 Team have been very busy, not only training but also working on the more intricate details of being an Ironman. </P>
<P>An information evening on the 28<SUP>th</SUP> August covered the important subject of nutrition. Coach, James Cunnama covered daily nutrition as well as training nutrition. Nutrition is often seen as the 4<SUP>th</SUP> discipline of Ironman. By the time that the FinishLine 2009 Team hear the gun go off on race day, they will know exactly how, when and where they have to feed their bodies for a perfect race.</P>
<P>Sunday the 31<SUP>st</SUP> August the FinishLine Team got together at the UPE grass track for a run clinic. IMSA Race Director, Paul Wolff and Elite Triathlete and Coach, James Cunnama started off with the importance of correct running form. A quick warm up and Paul then covered the importance of correct stretching. He then moved on to important running drills. The FinishLine Team then had to perform these drills under the supervision of Paul and James. To end the run clinic both Paul and James ran with each team member, analyzed their running style and showed them how to improve. The run clinic was a huge success and enormous fun. Triangle Institute has had several requests from Ironmen and runners for more clinics. Planning has started and dates will soon be decided on. </P>
    <a href="http://newsletters.onlineinnovations.com/ironman/newsletter.asp?NewsletterID=8433&ArticleID=8433">read more...</a>
